        "label": "What's Going On With the Commanders",
        "body": "Eight days. That&rsquo;s all that stands between the Washington Commanders and the moment they remake their roster at the podium in Pittsburgh. With a 5-12 season in the rearview and the third-place finish in the NFC East a bitter reminder of unmet expectations, the front office is in full evaluation mode&mdash;and the chatter around the No. 7 overall pick is intensifying. <strong>The Commanders have been hosting receivers in rapid succession this week, signaling a clear priority: adding a legitimate complement to Terry McLaurin on the perimeter.</strong> Names like Carnell Tate, Makai Lemon, and Omar Cooper Jr. have cycled through the facility, each one a potential answer to an offense that sputtered when McLaurin couldn&rsquo;t carry the load alone. The secondary remains a question mark too&mdash;Nick Cross and Will Harris are adequate starters at safety, but neither inspires confidence. With six total picks spanning three days of the draft, the Commanders have ammunition to reshape this roster. <strong>Watch whether general manager Adam Peters stays disciplined at seven or trades down for depth&mdash;this draft class is deep, and patience could yield better value on Day Two.</strong>",
        "updated": "Updated April 15, 2026"
      },
